📊 2. RescueTime

Best for: Passive automatic tracking without timers
Platform: Mac, Windows, Android (no iOS), browser extension

🔹 Features:

  • Tracks which apps, websites, and tools you use and for how long

✅ Pros:

  • No need to click anything — just let it run

  • Great for identifying time drains

  • Encourages digital wellbeing (focus sessions, goal nudges)

❌ Cons:

  • Less useful for specific project tracking

  • Doesn’t track paper work or non-digital activity

  • No iOS support

🗂️ 3. Clockify

Best for: Structured project/client-based time logging

Yes, Toggl Track can integrate with Notion, allowing you to synchronize time tracking with your Notion workspace. While there's no direct native integration, you can connect them using third-party automation tools.

🔄 Integration Options

1. Zapier (Free Plan Available)

Zapier enables you to automate workflows between Toggl Track and Notion without coding. For example, you can set up a "Zap" that creates a new Notion database item whenever a new time entry is added in Toggl Track. This helps in maintaining a centralized log of your time tracking within Notion. albato.com+6zapier.com+6toolfinder.co+6

2. Make (formerly Integromat) (Free Plan Available)

Make offers a visual interface to create complex integrations between Toggl Track and Notion. You can design workflows that, for instance, append Toggl time tracking reports to Notion databases, providing detailed insights into your time allocation across projects. reddit.com+2make.com+2toolfinder.co+2

3. Integrately (Free Plan Available)

Integrately provides one-click automation setups between Toggl Track and Notion. It's suitable for users seeking quick and straightforward integrations, such as creating a Toggl time entry when a new item is added in Notion. integrately.comintegrately.com+2toolfinder.co+2zapier.com+2

🧠 Considerations

  • No Native Integration: Toggl Track doesn't offer a built-in integration with Notion; third-party tools are necessary.

  • Free Plans: All the mentioned tools offer free tiers, which are generally sufficient for individual use.

  • Setup Complexity: While Zapier and Integrately are user-friendly, Make provides more advanced features for complex workflows.integrately.com+2make.com+2reddit.com+2

If you need assistance setting up any of these integrations or tailoring them to your specific workflow, feel free to ask!

You said:
idle detection
ChatGPT said:

Great — idle detection is one of Toggl Track’s most useful features for staying accurate. It helps when you forget to stop a timer or walk away from the computer.

💤 What Idle Detection Does

  • Toggl monitors your keyboard and mouse activity

  • If you’ve been inactive for a set period (e.g., 5 minutes), it will ask:

    “You’ve been idle. Do you want to discard this time, keep it, or edit it?”

Perfect if you get pulled into something or step away unexpectedly.

✅ How to Turn On Idle Detection (Mac Desktop App)

  1. Open Toggl Track desktop app

  2. Click the ⚙️ gear icon → go to Preferences

  3. Under Reminders, check:

    • ✅ Detect idle time

    • Set Idle after: 5 minutes is a good starting point

    • Choose your preferred action when idle is detected (Ask, Discard, etc.)

🧠 Tip:

  • If you do long sessions of reading or working in one window (like ChatGPT), idle detection might think you’re inactive. You can either:

    • Increase the idle timeout (e.g., 10–15 min)

    • Manually adjust the time entry if it gets flagged by mistake

If the edit is visual (e.g., cropping a page or removing part of an image):

✂️ To Crop Part of a Page:

  3. Use the Rectangular Selection Tool

  4. Draw a box around the area you want to keep

  5. Go to Tools > Crop

  6. Save As or Export the new version

⚠️ Note: This works best for image-based PDFs. If it’s vector-based (from a CAD export), Preview might not crop as cleanly.

  • pdfcandy.com

  1. Open Keynote

  2. Drag the PDF page into a blank slide

  3. Use white boxes to cover the parts you want to remove (e.g. 2nd half of house)

  4. Export the slide as a new PDF

  1. Download and install LibreOffice

  2. Open the PDF in LibreOffice Draw

  3. Edit vector shapes and remove unwanted elements directly

  4. Export to PDF again

Excellent and important question. Let’s clarify.

🧭 What Counts as Wohnfläche (Austria Standard Practice)?

Under Austrian norms (Wohnflächenverordnung, based on the German model), Wohnfläche (WF) includes:

✅ Typically Counted:

  • Living rooms, bedrooms, kitchens

  • Bathrooms, toilets

  • Entrance hallways, corridors

  • Utility rooms if heated and finished

  • Storage rooms within the living unit if finished

  • Stairways within the unit (partially)

❌ Not Counted as Wohnfläche:

  • Garages, carports

  • Basements (unless fully finished, heated, and with natural light)

  • Attics/lofts without full ceiling height (under 2m = 0%)

  • Technikräume, Heizräume, Pelletsräume

  • Exterior storage or sheds

  • Shared stairwells or corridors

🔎 In Our Case:

The current Wohnfläche total of 244.37 m² includes some borderline or possibly non-WF rooms that I flagged as “not obviously non-livable,” but they still might not qualify under strict legal WF rules.

  3. Potentially exclude:

# melody_utils.py

def reverse_melody(melody):
    """Return the melody reversed (retrograde)."""
    return melody[::-1]

def reflect_melody(melody, axis_pitch):
    """
    Reflects each note in melody over the given axis_pitch.
    Example: axis = 64, note = 62 → reflection = 66
    """
    return [axis_pitch + (axis_pitch - note) for note in melody]

📄 3. harmony_utils.py – Starting Template

python
# harmony_utils.py

def parallel_sixth_below(melody):
    """Return a harmony voice a major 6th below each melody note."""
    return [note - 9 for note in melody]  # 9 semitones = major sixth

def closest_triad_below(melody, triad_notes):
    """
    For each melody note, return the closest triad note *below* it.
    If no triad note is lower, returns the lowest triad note.
    """
    harmony = []
    for note in melody:
        below = [t for t in triad_notes if t < note]
        if below:
            harmony.append(max(below))
        else:
            harmony.append(min(triad_notes))
    return harmony

🔧 Step 2: Create a new file called harmony_utils.py

Paste into harmony_utils.py:

python
from tintharm import note_to_midi, midi_to_note, get_scale_notes, get_triad, get_triad_note

def harmonize_melody(melody_note, key='C', mode='major', tintinnabuli_levels=[-1], extra_m_intervals=[]):
    try:
        midi_val = note_to_midi(melody_note)
    except:
        return {"Error": f"Invalid melody note: {melody_note}"}

    scale = get_scale_notes(key, mode)
    if not scale:
        return {"Error": f"Unsupported key or mode: {key} {mode}"}
    triad = get_triad(scale)

    result = {'M': melody_note}

    for interval in extra_m_intervals:
        label = f"M{interval:+}"
        result[label] = midi_to_note(midi_val + interval)

    for level in tintinnabuli_levels:
        if level < 0:
            tn = get_triad_note(scale[0], triad, abs(level), direction='below')
            if tn:
                result[f"T{level}"] = tn
        else:
            tn = get_triad_note(scale[0], triad, level, direction='above')
            if tn:
                result[f"T{level}"] = tn
    return result

python
from your_main_module import note_to_midi, midi_to_note, get_scale_notes, get_triad, get_triad_note

def harmonize_melody(melody_note, key='C', mode='major', tintinnabuli_levels=[-1], extra_m_intervals=[]):
    try:
        midi_val = note_to_midi(melody_note)
    except:
        return {"Error": f"Invalid melody note: {melody_note}"}

    scale = get_scale_notes(key, mode)
    if not scale:
        return {"Error": f"Unsupported key or mode: {key} {mode}"}
    triad = get_triad(scale)

    result = {'M': melody_note}

    for interval in extra_m_intervals:
        label = f"M{interval:+}"
        result[label] = midi_to_note(midi_val + interval)

    for level in tintinnabuli_levels:
        if level < 0:
            tn = get_triad_note(scale[0], triad, abs(level), direction='below')
            if tn:
                result[f"T{level}"] = tn
        else:
            tn = get_triad_note(scale[0], triad, level, direction='above')
            if tn:
                result[f"T{level}"] = tn
    return result
